node.text:
What an incredible honor it was to meet a firefighter who charged into harm's way, fully expecting to die in the process, hell-bent on saving as many lives as he could. This is what heroism looks like. Thank you, Bobby Senn, for sharing your story with us.

It's been 20 long years since 9/11, and so much has happened. So much has changed, so many lives have been lost in the conflict that followed, and so much has been gained as well. We hope you take this day to remember the terrible loss our country sustained two decades ago, and that you use that somber reality to fuel you in life as you move forward. To live a full, honest, and positive life.

Our nation mourns still, yes, but none more than the loved ones of those who lost someone dear that day. Our hearts have extended to you all since the day the towers fell, and they extend to you again today.

For those of you who struggle today, who feel the looming weight of grief on your shoulders, we offer you a few words of encouragement:
"We must risk delight. We can do without pleasure,
but not delight. Not enjoyment. We must have
the stubbornness to accept our gladness in the ruthless
furnace of this world. To make injustice the only
measure of our attention is to praise the Devil."
- Jack Gilbert, A Brief For The Defense

node.text:
Guys like Wali, Afghan commandos, have spent their lives fighting for Afghanistan. They've stood side-by-side with their American counterparts in support of freedom and individual liberties. Now they're out there again fighting for their lives, and our hearts break for the unimaginable losses that have already been sustained. We're happy that Wali and a few others have made it here to the United States, and we hope that more will find a way.

@wtasleem

node.text:
It's the 77th anniversary of D-Day, where we reflect upon what was lost and what was gained during that fateful time in history. We all ought remember the sacrifices made and ask ourselves: how do we measure up to that? How do we make the efforts of those heroic men worth it?

@coffeeordiemag

node.text:
Today we remember those lost on that day:
U.S. Air Force Technical Sergeant John A. Chapman
⁣
Navy SEAL Petty Officer 1st Class Neil “Fifi” C. Roberts⁣
⁣
Air Force Pararescueman Senior Airman Jason D. Cunningham⁣
⁣
160th Special Operations Aviation Regiment (SOAR) Sergeant Philip “Spytech” Svitak⁣
⁣
Corporal Matthew A. Commons⁣
⁣
Sergeant Bradley S. Crose⁣
⁣
Specialist Marc A. Anderson⁣
Two Medals of Honor were awarded for actions taken that day, one to Air Force Combat Controller Tech. Sgt John A. Chapman (posthumously) and the other to Senior Chief Special Warfare Operator Britt K. Slabinski. Our guys at @coffeeordiemag had the distinct honor of speaking to one of the Rangers who fought on "Roberts Ridge" — check out the link in their bio (or head to our stories) to read the whole thing.

node.text:
What an incredible honor it was to meet a firefighter who charged into harm's way, fully expecting to die in the process, hell-bent on saving as many lives as he could. This is what heroism looks like. Thank you, Bobby Senn, for sharing your story with us.

It's been 20 long years since 9/11, and so much has happened. So much has changed, so many lives have been lost in the conflict that followed, and so much has been gained as well. We hope you take this day to remember the terrible loss our country sustained two decades ago, and that you use that somber reality to fuel you in life as you move forward. To live a full, honest, and positive life.

Our nation mourns still, yes, but none more than the loved ones of those who lost someone dear that day. Our hearts have extended to you all since the day the towers fell, and they extend to you again today.

For those of you who struggle today, who feel the looming weight of grief on your shoulders, we offer you a few words of encouragement:
"We must risk delight. We can do without pleasure,
but not delight. Not enjoyment. We must have
the stubbornness to accept our gladness in the ruthless
furnace of this world. To make injustice the only
measure of our attention is to praise the Devil."
- Jack Gilbert, A Brief For The Defense

node.text:
Our country was built by countless hardworking Americans, tough men and women who overcame incredible adversity to support their families and pursue a happy life. CHEERS to every one of you, keeping our country running. We hope we can keep y'all fueled up with great coffee while you fuel our nation and push it forward. #laborday

The United States is imperfect, and its history involves unimaginable suffering on so many levels — but we have prevailed due to one trait, a trait embodied by the working class of Americans since day one: perseverance. Perseverance to push through that daily grind in order to build something greater than yourself. Perseverance to put personal comfort aside in the name of a better life for your loved ones. Perseverance to take the sh*t hand you've been dealt and work with what you've got, because you hope for a brighter future.

It's this perseverance, born from the rough hands of rough Americans, that has provided most of the great things this country has to offer.

node.text:
What drool factor does this rate? 1-10, 10 meaning maximum drool.

Checkin' out that coffee? Our latest Exclusive Coffee Subscription coffee, Pink 79, is LIVE to ECS members for a limited time only! While it pairs while with great, homemade, backcountry pizza, that's cheating because judging by the look of this food... just about anything would pair well with it.

Like the iconic M79 Thumper, Pink 79 brings you an explosive coffee experience. In a good way. This light Ethiopian Wush Wush roast was sourced from the very birthplace of coffee. Best brewed via Aeropress, Patio Pour Over, and Chemex, those willing to wield this powerful micro lot will be treated to berry aromas and exotic notes of papaya, lime, and maple syrup.

Members of the Exclusive Coffee Subscription (ECS) are eligible to get new, micro-lot coffees every single month. The designs are super fun and a few of them have become kind of iconic in BRCC circles, but the real magic is in the coffee itself. These are rare coffees originating from all over the world. Anyone who appreciates a great cup of coffee will definitely love these. Speaking of, if you're interested in diving deeper into the coffee rabbithole, check out @brcc_coffeeheads 

📸: @mountainginger.adv 

For all things BRCC Outdoors: @brcc_outdoors

A long, difficult chapter in American history has come to an end. Still, there is a lot of work to do.

We have to make sure those who fought are taken care of, and that their families are taken care of as well. We have to learn from history and prevent the same mistakes from happening again. We have to unite to support the organizations who are still doing great work with those who stood next to us in Afghanistan for the last two decades. We have to make our voice heard and let our officials know that leaving Americans behind is unacceptable, and we have to support those getting them out.

There is a lot of work to do.

If you want to stay informed, we’re updating folks on the situation as it develops on @coffeeordiemag. One of the most recent endeavors there is to tell the individual stories of each service member killed in action. We can’t stress the importance of those stories being told and circulated.
